extended_information.full_description:
[http-cache-semantics](https://www.npmjs.com/package/http-cache-semantics) is a Node.js library that provides utilities for parsing, analyzing, and manipulating HTTP caching headers, based on the specifications defined in RFC7234. It helps developers to work with caching headers more efficiently and correctly.

A flaw was identified in `http-cache-semantics` whereby an unlimited amount of memory could be used when handling payloads with numerous repeating whitespaces. This could result in a denial-of-service attack due to excessive memory consumption.

The problem arises within the `parseCacheControl` function, where an insecure regex is utilized to trim whitespaces from an HTTP Header. To take advantage of this issue, an attacker needs to submit an HTTP Request that contains a specially-crafted `Cache-Control` header. This header should begin and end with any non-whitespace character, and contain a substantial number of spaces in between.

Exploit payload example- 
```
const payload = "A" + " ".repeat(10**5) + "B";
const CachePolicy = require("http-cache-semantics");
new CachePolicy({ headers: { "cache-control": payload, },}, { headers: {}, });

```

extended_information.remediation:
##### Development mitigations

Limit the amount of allowed whitespace in incoming requests -
```js
const WHITESPACE_LIMIT = 1000
if (request.headers["cache-control"].match(/\s/g).length > WHITESPACE_LIMIT) {
    // Error due to excessive whitespace
    return
}
cachePolicy = new CachePolicy(request, response); 
```

##### Development mitigations

Add a sanitization check for the following payloads:

* `127.1`, `127.0.1`, `127.00.0x1`, `127.0.0x0.1`
* `01200034567`
* `012.1.2.3`
* `fe80::0001`, `000:0:0000::01`, `000:0:0000:0:000:0:00:001`
* `::fFFf:127.0.0.1`

```
var ip = require('ip');

// Sanitization check before calling the vulnerable isPublic() function
if (userSuppliedIP === <payload>) {
    userSuppliedIP = "127.0.0.1";
}

// Safe call to the vulnerable functions
ip.isPublic(userSuppliedIP);
ip.isPrivate(userSuppliedIP);
ip.isLoopback(userSuppliedIP);
```

##### Development mitigations

Do not allow the `/` character in locales passed to `moment.locale()` -
```js
if (localeName.indexOf('/') !== -1) {
  return err;
}
...
moment.locale(localeName);
...
```

extended_information.full_description:
[multer](https://expressjs.com/en/resources/middleware/multer.html) is a node.js [middleware](https://expressjs.com/en/guide/using-middleware.html) designed to work with the [express.js](https://expressjs.com/) backend framework. It is intended for handling `multipart/form-data`, which is primarily used for uploading files.

The usage of multer is simple - users define certain express.js endpoints for file uploads, and whenever a `multipart/form-data` encoded request is provided to one of these endpoints by a client, multer handles the parsing of the request. For example:

```js 
const express = require('express');
const multer = require('multer');
const app = express();

const upload = multer({ dest: 'uploads/' });

app.post('/upload-profile-pic', upload.single('profilePicture'), (req, res) => {
  // user logic for handling the uploaded file
});

app.listen(3000, () => console.log('Server running on port 3000'));
```
This is a simple example of using multer to handle file upload endpoints. Essentially, whenever a post request with `multipart/form-data` encoding is sent to the `/upload-profile-pic` endpoint, multer handles most of the work and lets the user write only their custom logic.

When a `multipart/form-data` encoded request with an empty string file name is handled by multer, the express server crashes - causing denial of service. Attackers could use this to crash servers remotely simply by providing a file upload endpoint with an empty file name.
